title: Add support for Python 3.8+ on Windows when CUDA is enabled
body:
**Description**: Enable using onnxruntime-gpu on Windows with Python 3.8+

**Motivation and Context**
- Due to a breaking change in Python 3.8 the system PATH is no longer searched when loading a DLL. This prevented loading of CUDA and cuDNN DLLs.
- In Python 3.8+ this is handled by explicitly adding the path to DLLs using `os.add_dll_directory()`.
- CUDA Toolkit is expected to be installed on the system by using NVIDIA's official installer.
- cuDNN is expected to be installed on the system by following the [official installation instructions](https://docs.nvidia.com/deeplearning/cudnn/install-guide/index.html#install-windows), i.e. to be at the same location as CUDA Toolkit.
- CUDA/cuDNN version is currently hard-coded to default versions used in CI. Supporting any version would require broader changes in the code.

title: save data to and load data from an hdf5 file for checkpointing
body:
**Description**: Implementation of internal utility functions for saving to and loading from hdf5 file. These functions are useful for ```ORTTrainer``` checkpointing functionality.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
These changes are required to save and load an ```ORTTrainer``` checkpoint to and from an hdf5 file. 
  - More details on why hdf5 file format is required for ```ORTTrainer``` checkpointing:

    The main reason for a special file format is related to distributed training. In a distributed training scenario, each worker (or process) would write its own states to an output file. It is important to map each checkpoint file to its original rank along with the distributed environment training configuration, such as world size and type of distributed training. The existing checkpoint design embeds such information on filenames (e.g. common prefix along with world_rank, workd_size and other such parameters (encoded as strings) on the file name). This is necessary in order to correctly identify the rank of the file being loaded so it can be loaded into the corresponding trainer or to aggregate all checkpoints in proper order. But naming the files as such has certain drawbacks:
    - File names cannot be changed, affecting future extensions and BC concerns.
    - All checkpoint files need to reside in the same folder.
    - Since there is a default prefix name is hardcoded in the API, the file can be easily mistakenly overwritten.
    - Rank, world size and other ZeRO information is embedded in the file name.

    The proposal is to embed relevant metadata inside the file, which could have any friendly name as per the users liking. While loading, each file is partially read to build a map. Using pickle is avoided because it would require loading the entire checkpoint file (which could be huge) and discarding it in case it does not align with the one we are looking for. Here is where hdf5 comes into play. Hdf5 file format allows us to read only a part of the file (relevant metadata). This should enable us to build the rank to file name map fast and easily.

title: Moving from v1.5.1-cuda10.2-cudnn8 to v1.5.2-cuda10.2-cudnn8 downgrades Python and removes nvcc
body:
**Describe the bug**
The image tagged `v1.5.1-cuda10.2-cudnn8` reports Python 3.7.0 and has NVCC in the PATH. However, upgrading to `v1.5.2-cuda10.2-cudnn8` downgrades Python to 3.6.9 and removes nvcc.

**Urgency**
This breaks my previously-building container, and might break others'. Not an enormous issue, but worth looking into.

**System information**
- Building Docker image on Amazon Linux
- Using `mcr.microsoft.com/azureml/onnxruntime` container registry

**To Reproduce**
```bash
# v1.5.1: Python 3.7.0
docker run -it mcr.microsoft.com/azureml/onnxruntime:v1.5.1-cuda10.2-cudnn8 python3 --version

# v1.5.2: Python 3.6.9
docker run -it mcr.microsoft.com/azureml/onnxruntime:v1.5.2-cuda10.2-cudnn8 python3 --version

# v1.5.1: Release 10.2
docker run -it mcr.microsoft.com/azureml/onnxruntime:v1.5.1-cuda10.2-cudnn8 nvcc --version

# v1.5.2: Executable file not found
docker run -it mcr.microsoft.com/azureml/onnxruntime:v1.5.2-cuda10.2-cudnn8 nvcc --version
```

**Expected behavior**
Python version and nvcc presence remain consistent through patch releases.

title: Inconsistent inference time between C Python API [Megatron-LM]
body:
**Describe the bug**
The Python API appears to both be faster and consume more GPU memory than the C API. When looking at the verbose logs I was able to see a difference in the operations such that the **python API had fewer ops on the CPU**. This points to a missing optimization in the C API even when using ORT_ENABLE_ALL. 

**Urgency**
Likely impacts performance across multiple models. I was able to reproduce this using the onnx model for https://github.com/NVIDIA/Megatron-LM model. 

**System information**
- Linux Ubuntu 18.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from: Python pip / Source for C API
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.5.2
- Python version: 3.7
- GCC/Compiler version: 7.5.0
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 11.1 / 8.0.4.30
- GPU model and memory: TITAN V 12GB

**To Reproduce**
The [Megatron-LM repo](https://github.com/NVIDIA/Megatron-LM) above gives detailed steps to reproduce the Pytorch model (with the checkpoints in the repository). 
Then convert the model from [pytorch to onnx](https://pytorch.org/tutorials/advanced/super_resolution_with_onnxruntime.html) using  
```
torch.onnx.export(...)
```

I used `onnxruntime_perf_test` and `onnx_run_test` (-e cuda) to capture the performance of the C API and the script below for the Python API. The log for the C API is here: [log.txt](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/5637946/log.txt)

It is clear that several ops are running on the CPU and cannot be run on GPU and log the following error:
```
Force fallback to CPU execution provider for Op type: ...
```

- onnxruntime_run_test.py


```
import numpy as np
import onnxruntime as ort

modelName = 'megatron_gpt2_onnx/1/model.onnx'

inputs = []
shape_inp = [4, 1024]
shape_mask = [4, 1, 1024, 1024]

input_ids = np.zeros(shape_inp, np.int64)
segment_ids = np.zeros(shape_inp, np.int64)
input_mask = np.zeros(shape_mask, np.bool)

sess = ort.InferenceSession(modelName)
print(sess.get_providers())

input_names = sess.get_inputs()
print([inn.name for inn in input_names])

# Run 5 times to get accurate performance numbers
for _ in range(5):
    prob = sess.run(None, {'masked_input':input_ids, 'input.1':segment_ids, 'mask':input_mask})

print("RES", prob[0].shape)

```

- _Attach the ONNX model to the issue (where applicable) to expedite investigation_:  If needed I can share the model file as well.

**Expected behavior**
Similar logs and Identical distribution of operations in both C and Python API. [If not similar performance]

var so = SessionOptions.MakeSessionOptionWithCudaProvider(0);
